  <section class="pp-prose pp-prose-pink" aria-label="On the color">
    <p>In 1979 the psychologist <span class="pp-em">Alexander Schauss</span> persuaded the wardens at a Seattle naval brig to paint a holding cell <em>this</em> color. He reported that fifteen minutes of exposure reduced strength and aggression in agitated detainees. The Navy adopted it. So did county jails. So did at least one university football team, which painted the visiting locker room in it.</p>

    <p>The claim was that Baker-Miller pink lowered heart rate, drained aggression from the muscles, and produced a measurable sedative effect within minutes. The mechanism was a guess: the eye reads pink as a non-threat, the autonomic system follows.</p>

    <p>The replications mostly didn&rsquo;t. Controlled studies find no reliable effect of pink rooms over any other. What kept <span class="pp-em">drunk-tank pink</span> in use wasn&rsquo;t the data. It was a confident researcher, motivated wardens, no blinding.</p>

    <p>And yet you are <em>in</em> the color right now. Stay here another twenty seconds. Don&rsquo;t scroll yet.</p>
  </section>

  <button class="pp-cta" type="button" data-pp-reveal>Reveal what your retina is doing</button>

  <section class="pp-prose pp-prose-gray" aria-label="On the afterimage" hidden>
    <p>That cyan-green wash you are seeing on this gray field — it is not on the screen. It is in you.</p>
    <p>Your retina has two color-opponent channels: red/green and blue/yellow. On the red/green channel, the cells that fire for red and the cells that fire for green pull against each other. For the last minute or so you have been staring at a color that mostly pulled the red end. Those cells have <em>adapted</em>. Their gain has dropped. With the pink gone, the green cells, briefly unopposed, paint a cyan ghost on the gray.</p>
    <p>The mechanism is <span class="pp-em">chromatic adaptation</span>. It runs on every healthy retina, every time. The pink calming effect may or may not be real. This is happening as you read this sentence.</p>
    <p>The strongest evidence that color does something to your nervous system is not in the prison cell studies. It is the cyan you are looking at right now, which <em>is not on the screen</em>. You are reading it off your own retina.</p>
  </section>

